SIMPLE: wedding
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wedding
<hw>Wed"ding</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>wedding</ets>.]</ety> <def>Nuptial ceremony; nuptial festivities;
marriage; nuptials.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Simple and brief was the <qex>wedding</qex>, as that of Ruth and
of Boaz.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Certain anniversaries of an unbroken marriage have
received fanciful, and more or less appropriate, names. Thus, the fifth
anniversary is called the <xex>wooden wedding</xex>; the tenth, the
<xex>tin wedding</xex>; the fifteenth, the <xex>crystal wedding</xex>;
the twentieth, the <xex>china wedding</xex>; the twenty-fifth, the
<xex>silver wedding</xex>; the fiftieth, the <xex>golden wedding</xex>;
the sixtieth, the <xex>diamond wedding</xex>. These anniversaries are
often celebrated by appropriate presents of wood, tin, china, silver,
gold, etc., given by friends.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Wedding</xex> is often used adjectively; as,
<xex>wedding</xex> cake, <xex>wedding</xex> cards, <xex>wedding</xex>
clothes, <xex>wedding</xex> day, <xex>wedding</xex> feast,
<xex>wedding</xex> guest, <xex>wedding</xex> ring, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let her beauty be her <qex>wedding</qex> dower.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wedding favor</b></col>, <cd>a marriage favor. See under
<er>Marriage</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weder</ent>⟦br⟧
